Boats Segmentation: Factor Analysis

Jekin Patel, Ido NAFTALY, Philippe Ahn, Daniel Lu

Business Decisions

Creeqboat want to expand its North American market by focusing on its most important segments. Our team decided that the most effective way to do that was to keep a lower number of factors in our analysis as we are most interested in large segment behavior, rather than niche populations.

Our decision was to use 6 factors, named as follows:

  1. Boating as Leisure
  2. Boat Enthusiast
  3. Status Loving
  4. Brand Conscious
  5. Value Chasing
  6. Handy Man

The questions tied to each factor are:
1. Q1 21 Boating.helps.me.escape.from.everyday.life.and.relax
2. Q1 27 Boating.is.the.number.one.thing.I.do.with.my.spare.time
3. Q1 9 I.see.my.boat.as.a.status.symbol
4. Q1 4 I.only.consider.buying.a.boat.from.a.reputable.brand
5. Q1 2 When.buying.a.boat..getting.the.lowest.price.is.more.important.than.the.boat.brand
6. Q1 11 I.tend.to.perform.minor.boat.repairs.and.maintenance.on.my.own

The Data

We used the data containing answers to the “Attributes” section of the Creeqboat survey to segment respondants. These 29 questions were most relevant to obtain behavioral information about boat owners.

This is how the first 50 data looks:

Our Approach

Factor Analysis in 6 steps

  1. Confirm the data in metric

  2. Decide whether to scale or standardize the data

  3. Check the correlation matrix to see if Factor Analysis makes sense

  4. Develop a scree plot and decide on the number of factors to be derived

  5. Interpret the factors and consider factor rotations (technical but useful)

  6. Save factor scores for subsequent analyses

Let's follow these steps.

Step 2: Decide whether to scale or standardize the data

Our team decided not to scale or standardize the data for 3 reasons:
1. All questions were on the same scale
2. We were worried about losing mean information when standardizing
3. The standard deviations across the board were fairly regular, so there wasn't a strong need to perform this extra step

Step 3: Check correlation matrix to see if Factor Analysis makes sense

The correlation matrix of all 29 factor made sense as questions that intuitively seemed to have high correlation were in fact correlated. As such, we decided that this data was good to use.

This is the correlation matrix of the 29 original variable we use for factor analysis (Note: this would be the same for the standardized ones if the standardization is done as above; there is a mathematical reason for this that we will not explore - you could confirm it yourself):

5. Interpret the factors and consider factor rotations (technical but useful)

We decided to start with 5 factors because there were 5 factors with eigenvalue more than 1. However, after reviewing the components, we saw that the there were too many questions linked together with component 1 and thus, we lost information. Furthermore, we believed there were two dinstinct characteristics covered by that one factor.

Therefore, we increased the factor to 6. Though culmalative percentage of explained variance was still below 65%, the grouping of questions fit well together. We came up with 6 type of groups:
1. Boating as Leisure
2. Boat Enthusiast
3. Status Loving
4. Brand Conscious
5. Value Chasing
6. Handy Man


We also tried an analysis with 10 factors to cover a variance over 65%. However, we decided that this represented way too many factors. Going back to our business goal of targetting the main markets, we decided to aim for a smaller number of factors.

How would you interpret the selected factors?

Our factors clearly differentiate 6 separate behavioral factors:
1. Boating as Leisure: Positive about boating as an escape, to be with friends and relax
2. Boat Enthusiast: Love for boating and passionate about the sport
3. Status Loving: See boats as a status symbol and may want better performance or aesthetics
4. Brand Conscious: The brand is very important to them
5. Value Chasing: Conscious about both price and value.
6. Handy Man: Performs most minor repairs on the boat

Intepretation, Decisions and Conclusion

Our interpretation of the data was that it provided enough information to perform factor analysis. We aimed for a lower number of factors to simply the analysis and also target the larger consumer segments.

Our decision was to use 6 factors, named as follows:

  1. Boating as Leisure
  2. Boat Enthusiast
  3. Status Loving
  4. Brand Conscious
  5. Value Chasing
  6. Handy Man

The questions tied to each factor are:
1. Q1 21
2. Q1 27
3. Q1 9
4. Q1 4
5. Q1 2
6. Q1 11
